TAMZIN TAYLOR: So
the next session

00:00:02.400 --> 00:00:03.920
is about how to manage your CEO.

00:00:03.920 --> 00:00:06.390
So let me ask you
how many people--

00:00:06.390 --> 00:00:13.110
hands up if you're an
employee and not the CEO.

00:00:13.110 --> 00:00:16.500
Excellent, so
hopefully, you'll be

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:20.730
able to take away some
tangible lessons and tips

00:00:20.730 --> 00:00:23.670
that you can take to rein
those crazy people in.

00:00:28.630 --> 00:00:31.660
Who can empathize
with this meme?

00:00:31.660 --> 00:00:33.255
Hands up.

00:00:33.255 --> 00:00:33.755
Yeah.

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:42.580
Knowing how to handle the
prioritization of what

00:00:42.580 --> 00:00:46.570
to build in your product when
you have so many competing

00:00:46.570 --> 00:00:51.520
opinions, stakeholders,
self-interest,

00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:56.950
not to mention important
people like your CEO or CFO's

00:00:56.950 --> 00:01:01.150
very strong views, maybe on
the type of color of green,

00:01:01.150 --> 00:01:02.840
for example.

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:05.160
So how do you avoid
opinion-based product

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:07.000
prioritization?

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.300
Well, this was an
interest of mine,

00:01:10.300 --> 00:01:15.460
so a few months ago, I
interviewed about 15 to 20

00:01:15.460 --> 00:01:17.560
of our top developers.

00:01:17.560 --> 00:01:21.320
I interviewed Google engineers,
Google product managers,

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:22.670
directors of growth.

00:01:22.670 --> 00:01:25.660
And I tried to tease
out of them, how

00:01:25.660 --> 00:01:28.920
did they approach this problem?

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:31.020
And you know what
struck me was there

00:01:31.020 --> 00:01:35.350
were two key characteristics.

00:01:35.350 --> 00:01:41.130
The first is that successful
developers rely on data

00:01:41.130 --> 00:01:44.630
to make a call on what
to experiment on first

00:01:44.630 --> 00:01:46.800
and what to build.

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:49.440
And the second really
important factor

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:54.910
was that they had imbued this
culture of data and sharing

00:01:54.910 --> 00:01:58.800
of information throughout
their organization.

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:02.604
So to add color and
context of this discussion,

00:02:02.604 --> 00:02:04.020
in a few minutes,
I'll be inviting

00:02:04.020 --> 00:02:11.039
on stage both 1tap and 2017
app of the year winner Memrise

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:13.560
to share with us their
experiences on reigning

00:02:13.560 --> 00:02:16.939
in their crazy CEOs.

00:02:16.939 --> 00:02:18.480
I know one of them
is there laughing.

00:02:18.480 --> 00:02:19.920
He's not that crazy.

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:23.010
So let's get started
with prioritization.

00:02:23.010 --> 00:02:26.940
And just to note, the
models and suggestions

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:30.540
that we make here today are
just some of the best practices

00:02:30.540 --> 00:02:32.280
that you can use.

00:02:32.280 --> 00:02:34.790
So they're not the
only ones you can use,

00:02:34.790 --> 00:02:36.540
but hopefully, you'll
be able to take away

00:02:36.540 --> 00:02:37.890
some key nuggets of gold.

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:44.040
So just a few seconds
ago, many of you

00:02:44.040 --> 00:02:49.830
had put up your hands to say
that prioritization was hard.

00:02:49.830 --> 00:02:51.790
But it can be made
easier with data.

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:54.510
Thank you for reconfirming.

00:02:54.510 --> 00:02:59.250
So over the last month, I've
worked with the 1tap team

00:02:59.250 --> 00:03:04.380
to test out a model that
Google used internally

00:03:04.380 --> 00:03:08.280
for deciding how to
prioritize what we build.

00:03:08.280 --> 00:03:13.350
We use this model on
Allo, YouTube, Gmail,

00:03:13.350 --> 00:03:15.870
and we actually have
an internal growth

00:03:15.870 --> 00:03:19.830
team who gets a conduit out
to our different products.

00:03:19.830 --> 00:03:24.720
So I harnessed that team,
and we worked with 1tap.

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:27.100
Now, again, this is not
the only way to do it.

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:28.830
Bear with me.

00:03:28.830 --> 00:03:30.810
But if it gives you a
different perspective,

00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:32.470
this is a good thing.

00:03:32.470 --> 00:03:34.620
Now, before I introduce
John on stage,

00:03:34.620 --> 00:03:40.020
let me just give you a brief
overview of this Google model.

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:42.700
So as you can see,
it's pretty simple.

00:03:42.700 --> 00:03:44.790
It looks pretty simple.

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:47.060
It's made up of
four components--

00:03:47.060 --> 00:03:52.740
the North Star metric,
user flows, a growth model,

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:53.700
and a spreadsheet.

00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:57.750
Because, let's face
it, what database model

00:03:57.750 --> 00:04:01.490
would be complete
without a spreadsheet?

00:04:01.490 --> 00:04:06.370
Now, the model serves to help
you uncover opportunities,

00:04:06.370 --> 00:04:09.160
and more importantly, it serves
as a common communication

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:12.835
tool for your whole company to
talk about growth, products,

00:04:12.835 --> 00:04:15.650
and prioritization.

00:04:15.650 --> 00:04:18.620
So to kick off and go deeper on
this, the first one I mentioned

00:04:18.620 --> 00:04:20.600
was the North Star metric.

00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:23.120
Now, listening to
Anthony [INAUDIBLE] talk

00:04:23.120 --> 00:04:25.700
about behavioral
design, it struck me

00:04:25.700 --> 00:04:29.070
that we were talking about
the same thing, which

00:04:29.070 --> 00:04:33.180
is it's that key
engagement user metric.

00:04:33.180 --> 00:04:36.240
Now, the way that we
define a North Star metric

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:39.270
is that it
encapsulates everything

00:04:39.270 --> 00:04:43.200
that you do in your app, and
it encapsulates all the value

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:46.210
that you're providing to a user.

00:04:46.210 --> 00:04:51.750
So as an example, if anyone here
is staying at Airbnb this week,

00:04:51.750 --> 00:04:53.730
it would be nights booked.

00:04:53.730 --> 00:04:57.450
For WhatsApp, it would
be messages sent.

00:04:57.450 --> 00:04:59.519
So again, the purpose is
to create a shared goal

00:04:59.519 --> 00:05:01.810
across all of your different
divisions in your company,

00:05:01.810 --> 00:05:05.470
so they're all going
for the same goal.

00:05:05.470 --> 00:05:08.740
The next element is
mapping the user flows.

00:05:08.740 --> 00:05:12.410
Has anyone here mapped
their user flows?

00:05:12.410 --> 00:05:15.720
A few of you, good, so this
might be familiar to you.

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:19.130
The way that we approach it is
that, essentially, we define

00:05:19.130 --> 00:05:22.600
user flows as a visual
representation of your user

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:26.600
journeys throughout your app
across acquisition, engagement,

00:05:26.600 --> 00:05:28.610
conversion, and retention.

00:05:28.610 --> 00:05:33.220
And that flows from sources
of acquisition, critical user

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:37.990
journeys, you drill down on
some important aspects, perhaps

00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:43.290
your engagement activities,
and your retention activities.

00:05:43.290 --> 00:05:46.790
Now, I can see you
taking photos madly.

00:05:46.790 --> 00:05:49.140
The next bit's going to
really mess it up, so

00:05:49.140 --> 00:05:51.050
take your photo now.

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:52.970
Once you've mapped this out--

00:05:52.970 --> 00:05:54.440
and I quite like
the color coding.

00:05:54.440 --> 00:05:56.450
It helps me visualize it better.

00:05:56.450 --> 00:06:00.410
The next thing you want to do
is mess it up with some lines.

00:06:00.410 --> 00:06:04.100
So you stick in how
all of these components

00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:08.330
relate to one another, the
idea being that this will then

00:06:08.330 --> 00:06:11.000
show you where some
of the activities

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:14.210
are not supporting
the rest of the app

00:06:14.210 --> 00:06:16.990
and help you identify
opportunities to improve.

00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:18.850
Now, that's all
well and good, but I

00:06:18.850 --> 00:06:21.400
mentioned this was all
about data, didn't I?

00:06:21.400 --> 00:06:24.710
So what's missing here,
and which will really

00:06:24.710 --> 00:06:28.100
rely on you having a very
robust analytics system,

00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:31.310
is to put in the proportion
of users who are successfully

00:06:31.310 --> 00:06:34.250
going from step A to
step B, which will then

00:06:34.250 --> 00:06:37.310
allow you to see where the
weak points are in your flow.

00:06:37.310 --> 00:06:39.710
For example, there
might be some issues

00:06:39.710 --> 00:06:42.470
with return from
notifications and some issues

00:06:42.470 --> 00:06:44.150
with notification permission.

00:06:44.150 --> 00:06:46.800
You can draw a conclusion there.

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:49.910
So this mapping of
user flows really

00:06:49.910 --> 00:06:51.410
helps everyone in
your business talk

00:06:51.410 --> 00:06:53.120
about the product
in the same way

00:06:53.120 --> 00:06:55.940
and understand how
their activities impact

00:06:55.940 --> 00:06:59.630
the overall North Star metric.

00:06:59.630 --> 00:07:02.750
Once you've worked out where
your area for improvement is--

00:07:02.750 --> 00:07:06.650
I mentioned notifications was
something in this example--

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:12.140
then next step is to drill down
on what are the key levers that

00:07:12.140 --> 00:07:14.060
will impact that metric.

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:16.070
So in the case of
notifications, for example,

00:07:16.070 --> 00:07:18.680
we had average users opted in.

00:07:18.680 --> 00:07:20.360
We had average number
of notifications

00:07:20.360 --> 00:07:22.580
sent, and for example,
the click through rate

00:07:22.580 --> 00:07:23.860
of those notifications.

00:07:23.860 --> 00:07:26.870
This is not rocket science,
but just drawing it out

00:07:26.870 --> 00:07:31.070
helps everyone to be clear
on what the potential levers

00:07:31.070 --> 00:07:32.660
you have are.

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:35.790
Now, I mentioned
there's this need

00:07:35.790 --> 00:07:37.670
to have a spreadsheet
in here somewhere.

00:07:37.670 --> 00:07:39.770
So once you've mapped
out that subsection,

00:07:39.770 --> 00:07:42.770
transfer it to a spreadsheet,
link it all up together,

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:44.660
and you can run
scenario analysis

00:07:44.660 --> 00:07:46.790
to compare your
different competing ideas

00:07:46.790 --> 00:07:50.435
to see which one will have the
biggest impact on your North

00:07:50.435 --> 00:07:52.640
Star metric.

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:56.900
Now, to tell us more
about their experience--

00:07:56.900 --> 00:07:59.150
because as I said,
the North Star metric

00:07:59.150 --> 00:08:01.700
seems pretty simple,
but I think we

00:08:01.700 --> 00:08:05.220
know there's a lot more complex
thinking that goes into it--

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:08.060
I'd like to welcome on
stage John Butterfield, head

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:10.324
of growth of 1Tap.

00:08:10.324 --> 00:08:12.740
JON BUTTERFIELD: So one of the
things we did when we first

00:08:12.740 --> 00:08:16.400
started making this product
is focusing on analytics,

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:19.500
and we track everything a
user does within the app.

00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:23.240
And this is something that
we are really proud of,

00:08:23.240 --> 00:08:28.220
but we'll see how that unraveled
while working with Tamzin.

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:30.980
So the first thing we did,
as Tamzin showed you earlier,

00:08:30.980 --> 00:08:34.320
was we've created this user
flow, this thing up here.

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:36.380
This is about the
10th iteration of it.

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:40.250
The first one had thousands and
thousands of different things

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:45.080
in it, and it was
just a cluster thing.

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:46.100
I won't say the word.

00:08:46.100 --> 00:08:50.050
And so we dumbed
it down to this.

00:08:50.050 --> 00:08:52.550
And we actually worked
with the head of growth

00:08:52.550 --> 00:08:54.870
at Google on this one as well.

00:08:54.870 --> 00:08:58.100
And the thing he really
gave us as a key takeaway is

00:08:58.100 --> 00:09:01.190
don't include everything from
the app, just the key moments

00:09:01.190 --> 00:09:03.000
in the key journeys.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:04.670
And the first thing
listed for us,

00:09:04.670 --> 00:09:07.440
actually, was show that
we have some problems,

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:10.230
and it's at the end, that
weird mustardy colored bit,

00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:12.620
where it's essentially
like an exit point.

00:09:12.620 --> 00:09:16.820
The user journey doesn't
come all the way back around.

00:09:16.820 --> 00:09:23.300
So this was the first useful
part of building this model.

00:09:23.300 --> 00:09:26.084
So the next thing was about
the North Star metric.

00:09:26.084 --> 00:09:27.500
And now this is
an interesting one

00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:29.490
because, for us,
it's pretty simple.

00:09:29.490 --> 00:09:32.030
So our mission as a
company, as you can see,

00:09:32.030 --> 00:09:36.840
is to make being self-employed
easier than being employed.

00:09:36.840 --> 00:09:39.740
And so if we want
to make this easier,

00:09:39.740 --> 00:09:45.770
the best thing we can
do is, quite simple--

00:09:45.770 --> 00:09:48.790
there we go-- is
collect transactions.

00:09:48.790 --> 00:09:50.880
The more transactions
we collect for a user,

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:52.790
the more we can
provide value, and it's

00:09:52.790 --> 00:09:54.860
all about providing that value.

00:09:54.860 --> 00:09:58.900
So transactions per user is
a really easy one for us,

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:01.340
but then we break
it down per product.

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:04.160
So with 1tap receipts,
the obvious thing here

00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:09.424
is the transaction in that term
is a receipt, receipt per user.

00:10:09.424 --> 00:10:11.090
Now, the tricky part
here, and the thing

00:10:11.090 --> 00:10:15.500
that really threw us off,
was what's more important,

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:18.170
users adding a lot of receipts,
or a lot of uses just adding

00:10:18.170 --> 00:10:19.584
a few receipts?

00:10:19.584 --> 00:10:21.500
So again, you've got to
think about the value,

00:10:21.500 --> 00:10:24.980
and the value is, if
they give us more data,

00:10:24.980 --> 00:10:27.230
we can then help
them with their taxes

00:10:27.230 --> 00:10:30.470
and do everything for
them, essentially.

00:10:30.470 --> 00:10:34.381
So it is all about receipts
per user, and the more receipts

00:10:34.381 --> 00:10:34.880
the better.

00:10:37.254 --> 00:10:38.920
So then we put it
into our growth model.

00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:42.640
As you saw, it's this really
long document of all things--

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:45.440
the whole equation
of the growth model.

00:10:45.440 --> 00:10:48.190
So I didn't put all that in
because it's just too much

00:10:48.190 --> 00:10:50.350
and it's really boring.

00:10:50.350 --> 00:10:51.790
But when we first
wrote that out,

00:10:51.790 --> 00:10:53.830
it is about 16 pages
of this document,

00:10:53.830 --> 00:10:55.780
and it was just crazy.

00:10:55.780 --> 00:10:59.530
So again, we took the idea of
just dumbing it down and making

00:10:59.530 --> 00:11:02.330
it something that
anybody can understand.

00:11:02.330 --> 00:11:05.740
And the headline here was
Receipts Added Per User,

00:11:05.740 --> 00:11:08.710
and it's broken down by
the [INAUDIBLE] divided

00:11:08.710 --> 00:11:11.800
by the receipt submissions.

00:11:11.800 --> 00:11:14.464
And then it's the receipt
submissions, as you can see,

00:11:14.464 --> 00:11:15.880
are defined by the
different entry

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:19.570
points and new and
returning users.

00:11:19.570 --> 00:11:22.084
So what was interesting
in here-- as I said,

00:11:22.084 --> 00:11:24.250
we're really proud of the
analytics and the tracking

00:11:24.250 --> 00:11:27.550
that we put in within the app.

00:11:27.550 --> 00:11:29.450
But while we started
working on this,

00:11:29.450 --> 00:11:31.540
we suddenly realized, hang on,
we're not tracking this, this,

00:11:31.540 --> 00:11:32.956
and this, and these
are all things

00:11:32.956 --> 00:11:35.050
that provide value
and make it easier

00:11:35.050 --> 00:11:38.609
for us to deliver our
North Star metric.

00:11:38.609 --> 00:11:40.150
So suddenly, it made
us realize we've

00:11:40.150 --> 00:11:45.070
got to go back and update our
analytics and things like that.

00:11:45.070 --> 00:11:47.680
And with this growth model, one
of the most interesting things

00:11:47.680 --> 00:11:50.230
it did was that
it made it easier

00:11:50.230 --> 00:11:53.170
for us to explain to the CEO--

00:11:53.170 --> 00:11:55.450
who I won't bash in
this session today

00:11:55.450 --> 00:11:57.100
because he's sat right there.

00:11:57.100 --> 00:11:57.730
Hi, Nick.

00:11:57.730 --> 00:12:00.680
He's filming as well,
actually, which is even worse.

00:12:00.680 --> 00:12:03.970
So it made it so he could see
where the [INAUDIBLE] comes

00:12:03.970 --> 00:12:06.740
from, and then the CFO could
see where all the revenue comes

00:12:06.740 --> 00:12:07.240
from.

00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:09.160
And products, who is
also sitting there,

00:12:09.160 --> 00:12:13.000
could see what essentially
would work next to--

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.750
what levers to pull to get
the most amount of value.

00:12:17.750 --> 00:12:19.830
So then we put it
into this calculator--

00:12:19.830 --> 00:12:23.840
this growth model, spreadsheet.

00:12:23.840 --> 00:12:26.090
This is just the
first part of it,

00:12:26.090 --> 00:12:29.200
but again, you can see here,
with the starting values,

00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:32.127
essentially what
happens over 10 days.

00:12:32.127 --> 00:12:33.460
And this is just the high level.

