00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:07.330
So we've been super
lucky with having

00:18:07.330 --> 00:18:12.560
one of the most creative and
experimental CEOs out there.

00:18:12.560 --> 00:18:17.080
It has its upsides, which means
that it's a great inspiration,

00:18:17.080 --> 00:18:22.430
and it injects a lot of creative
thinking and experimentalism

00:18:22.430 --> 00:18:24.700
to the rest of the team.

00:18:24.700 --> 00:18:28.840
The downside is that it kind
of sets a slightly different

00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:32.320
challenge for product
people and product team

00:18:32.320 --> 00:18:35.590
to manage the whole thing and
manage all these creative ideas

00:18:35.590 --> 00:18:38.650
coming out of the
brains like that.

00:18:38.650 --> 00:18:44.020
And as an example,
about two years ago,

00:18:44.020 --> 00:18:47.620
I got a text message
from Ed, our CEO,

00:18:47.620 --> 00:18:52.600
on Sunday morning, saying
that, good morning, Kristina.

00:18:52.600 --> 00:18:54.010
I'm in Scotland.

00:18:54.010 --> 00:18:57.040
I bought a double decker bus.

00:18:57.040 --> 00:18:59.230
I'm going to find
a repair man who

00:18:59.230 --> 00:19:04.030
is going to fix it, a
driver, and a film crew,

00:19:04.030 --> 00:19:08.560
and the bus is going to
tour the rest of the Europe

00:19:08.560 --> 00:19:12.640
filming videos of native
speakers saying phrases

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:15.400
and sentences in all these
different languages that

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:18.740
are spoken in these
European countries.

00:19:18.740 --> 00:19:22.690
So it was quite a
unique experience

00:19:22.690 --> 00:19:24.430
to get a message like that.

00:19:24.430 --> 00:19:28.630
And what happened was that
we had to come up ways

00:19:28.630 --> 00:19:31.630
how to handle these
kind of creative ideas

00:19:31.630 --> 00:19:35.110
and very often
slightly crazy ideas,

00:19:35.110 --> 00:19:37.780
and how to turn them
into successful features

00:19:37.780 --> 00:19:39.470
for our product.

00:19:39.470 --> 00:19:45.310
So what happened was we
had to come up with a way

00:19:45.310 --> 00:19:50.200
how to filter and how to assess
and measure such crazy ideas

00:19:50.200 --> 00:19:53.470
that not just the CEOs, but
also everyone in the team

00:19:53.470 --> 00:19:54.940
can come up with.

00:19:54.940 --> 00:19:57.680
And we kind of felt
like spreadsheets

00:19:57.680 --> 00:20:01.420
and different models
and frameworks

00:20:01.420 --> 00:20:03.160
and systems and
processes are maybe

00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:06.730
too harsh for filtering
out some genius

00:20:06.730 --> 00:20:09.940
pieces of creative glimpses.

00:20:09.940 --> 00:20:12.970
And we ended up
having and coming up

00:20:12.970 --> 00:20:18.400
with six criteria for how to
filter out useful ideas out

00:20:18.400 --> 00:20:20.710
of generic nonsense.

00:20:20.710 --> 00:20:24.070
And the six criteria
that we came up with

00:20:24.070 --> 00:20:27.280
was every single idea
has to be iterable,

00:20:27.280 --> 00:20:30.460
which means that we
should start small.

00:20:30.460 --> 00:20:34.090
We should take every
feature as an MVP

00:20:34.090 --> 00:20:37.600
and then iterate if
it is successful.

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:41.290
We think that the idea has
to have an immediate impact,

00:20:41.290 --> 00:20:43.540
so as soon as we
rollout the feature

00:20:43.540 --> 00:20:45.880
and launch it for
our users, we do

00:20:45.880 --> 00:20:48.610
want to see some kind
of behavioral change

00:20:48.610 --> 00:20:52.330
or some change in metrics.

00:20:52.330 --> 00:20:55.060
It has to have a
lasting effect, which

00:20:55.060 --> 00:21:00.730
means that one trick ponies
do not quite work for us.

00:21:00.730 --> 00:21:04.120
We do want to build features
that have an impact on language

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:06.010
learners for an
extended period of time,

00:21:06.010 --> 00:21:09.880
not just for the first five
minutes or the first day.

00:21:09.880 --> 00:21:13.090
Everything has to be
measurable, obviously.

00:21:13.090 --> 00:21:17.389
And it has to have a power
of localization, which

00:21:17.389 --> 00:21:18.930
I think, for a
language learning app,

00:21:18.930 --> 00:21:23.740
is maybe a unique but user
base for almost any app in--

00:21:23.740 --> 00:21:25.240
out there is very global.

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:28.810
So its good to benefit
from making sure

00:21:28.810 --> 00:21:30.430
that it works in
every single language

00:21:30.430 --> 00:21:33.460
for every culture for
right to left and left

00:21:33.460 --> 00:21:35.330
to right languages.

00:21:35.330 --> 00:21:37.510
And finally,
obviously, it all has

00:21:37.510 --> 00:21:41.950
to fit into a coherent product,
so even the craziest ideas just

00:21:41.950 --> 00:21:45.430
have to fit in somewhere
and make sense.

00:21:45.430 --> 00:21:49.400
And we went even deeper.

00:21:49.400 --> 00:21:53.050
So in order to keep this kind
of creative and experimental

00:21:53.050 --> 00:21:56.890
mindset in the company
and in every single team,

00:21:56.890 --> 00:22:00.820
we divided our product
development lifecycle

00:22:00.820 --> 00:22:04.630
into three stages, the first
one being the discovery stage

00:22:04.630 --> 00:22:06.490
where we prototype.

00:22:06.490 --> 00:22:07.480
We sketch.

00:22:07.480 --> 00:22:08.200
We design.

00:22:08.200 --> 00:22:09.100
We draw.

00:22:09.100 --> 00:22:12.160
We user test the idea.

00:22:12.160 --> 00:22:15.520
We build something that
we can get random people

00:22:15.520 --> 00:22:17.830
from the street to test it out.

00:22:17.830 --> 00:22:23.170
In the Memrise Membus
case, the discovery phase

00:22:23.170 --> 00:22:25.660
included sending the
bus to a mini trip

00:22:25.660 --> 00:22:28.750
to Oxford to film the
videos in English first

00:22:28.750 --> 00:22:31.150
to see whether this
makes any sense

00:22:31.150 --> 00:22:34.720
or not before touring
the rest of the Europe.

00:22:34.720 --> 00:22:41.200
And after doing the dry runs
and testing these ideas out,

00:22:41.200 --> 00:22:43.510
we define it in
a fairly detailed

00:22:43.510 --> 00:22:48.340
spec with all the
functionality described,

00:22:48.340 --> 00:22:51.970
everything, all the sketches,
all the designs drawn out.

00:22:51.970 --> 00:22:56.230
We do involve data team in
this stage of the process

00:22:56.230 --> 00:22:59.310
quite heavily because
we have to make sure

00:22:59.310 --> 00:23:02.520
that we build the feature
for the right user

00:23:02.520 --> 00:23:07.860
for the right use case, we
track and implement the data

00:23:07.860 --> 00:23:09.630
points in a correct way.

00:23:09.630 --> 00:23:13.500
So it's super important
that the data people

00:23:13.500 --> 00:23:15.930
are involved in the process.

00:23:15.930 --> 00:23:20.010
Once everything is
ready and set up,

00:23:20.010 --> 00:23:23.670
the development teams take
over and actually start

00:23:23.670 --> 00:23:25.650
building the features.

00:23:25.650 --> 00:23:29.440
Because everyone has been
quite nicely involved

00:23:29.440 --> 00:23:32.280
in the discovery and in
the definition phase,

00:23:32.280 --> 00:23:34.016
it's fairly easy
for the developers

00:23:34.016 --> 00:23:35.640
to understand why
we're building things

00:23:35.640 --> 00:23:39.240
and how exactly they
need to be built.

00:23:39.240 --> 00:23:43.560
From the product perspective, a
super key thing to keep in mind

00:23:43.560 --> 00:23:46.110
is that, even with the
most sophisticated systems

00:23:46.110 --> 00:23:50.310
and processes in place, it
even happens for the most

00:23:50.310 --> 00:23:53.520
experienced product managers
that you sometimes forget

00:23:53.520 --> 00:23:55.680
to switch on the
feature and experiment

00:23:55.680 --> 00:23:59.640
when it goes out, so that the
users will actually see what

00:23:59.640 --> 00:24:05.170
you built. And once
everything is nicely set up,

00:24:05.170 --> 00:24:09.310
and the new version
of the app is out,

00:24:09.310 --> 00:24:12.930
and now it's time to take
a photo of this as well,

00:24:12.930 --> 00:24:18.960
it's the joyful moment
of watching when and how

00:24:18.960 --> 00:24:22.110
the results come in.

00:24:22.110 --> 00:24:24.300
We are organized as
well, so it's not

00:24:24.300 --> 00:24:26.400
like we're all over the
place with crazy ideas.

00:24:26.400 --> 00:24:28.590
We have a standard
set of metrics,

00:24:28.590 --> 00:24:32.070
standard graphs for every
single experiment, AB test

00:24:32.070 --> 00:24:33.730
feature that goes out.

00:24:33.730 --> 00:24:38.160
And the day after the release
is like refreshing this page

00:24:38.160 --> 00:24:41.670
all the time, which is the
reasonable and sensible way

00:24:41.670 --> 00:24:47.430
to see how the feature and
the new idea has performed.

00:24:47.430 --> 00:24:51.550
In our team's case, it
shows you the joy and fun

00:24:51.550 --> 00:24:55.890
of seeing the results coming in
and learning whether we built

00:24:55.890 --> 00:24:58.350
something super successful
that people enjoy

00:24:58.350 --> 00:25:01.390
or whether we need to go
back to the whiteboard

00:25:01.390 --> 00:25:03.640
and sketch and start
thinking again.

00:25:03.640 --> 00:25:07.042
So I think EuroVision is
quite popular in Germany,

00:25:07.042 --> 00:25:09.000
so it's almost like
watching the results come--

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:12.000
votes coming in and then
seeing whether we're

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:13.770
on a winning in
case or losing case.

00:25:13.770 --> 00:25:16.920
So hopefully, this has
given you a few ideas

00:25:16.920 --> 00:25:20.610
how to do product prioritization
without spreadsheets as well,

00:25:20.610 --> 00:25:24.940
